  <article class="prose">
    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Supporting workbench · stipulate structure, project to text
    </div>
    <h1>MiniCausalLang — language structure with a known answer</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      A workbench for stipulating a formal-semantic object and checking whether a model recovers it.
    </p>

    <p>
      MiniCausalLang makes the program's question decidable rather than guessed: it starts from a
      <em>known formal-semantic object</em>, projects it to text by template, and asks whether a
      model's behavior is isomorphic to the object it was compiled from. Because the structure —
      and the full space of alternatives it licenses — is stipulated by construction, structure
      recovery can be scored against a known target. Its <strong>first domain is the causal graph</strong>
      (below); it is being generalised into a <strong>modal-semantic compiler</strong> — a candidate
      world-set plus a ◇/□ constraint, rendered in English, German, and Chinese, graded for
      whether the model tracks the surviving worlds — which is the version the modal-concepts thesis
      runs on.
    </p>

    <MiniCausalFigure />

    <p>
      The hard direction in my <a href="/writing/inferential-productivity">note on inferential
      productivity</a> is reverse: given a behavior, what is the <em>smallest</em> causal structure
      that has to be there? On a real model, there is usually no ground truth against which to score
      a recovered structure. MiniCausalLang keeps the bridge explicit before trusting the method
      elsewhere: specify the grammar, compile it into a causal graph, enumerate the inferences that
      graph licenses, train or evaluate a model on that data, and test whether behavioral recovery
      returns the structure that was actually planted.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is supporting infrastructure, not a paper in its own right. It exists to make the link
      between linguistic form and the formal-semantic structure it encodes — causal structure in the
      first domain, modal structure in the next — explicit enough to be falsifiable against a known
      answer.
    </p>

    <hr/>
    <p class="!text-sm !text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">An interactive workbench — specify a grammar, compile the graph, see what recovery returns — will live here.</p>
  </article>
</Base>
